<div class="container">
    
    <section>
        <h2>1. THE GREAT COSMIC MYSTERY</h2>
        <p>Imagine looking at a massive skyscraper and realizing that the bricks you see only account for 5% of its weight. The rest is held together by an invisible, undetectable framework. This is exactly how our universe works.</p>
        <p><span class="highlight">Dark Matter</span> is a mysterious substance that does not emit, absorb, or reflect light. We cannot see it with telescopes, yet it acts as the "gravitational glue" that prevents galaxies from flying apart.</p>
        
        
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>2. THE SMOKING GUN: SCIENTIFIC EVIDENCE</h2>
        <p>How do we know it's there if we can't see it? Astronomers have found "fingerprints" that prove its existence:</p>
        
        <h3>A. Galaxy Rotation Curves</h3>
        <p>In the 1970s, <strong>Vera Rubin</strong> discovered that stars at the edge of galaxies move just as fast as stars near the center. According to known physics, they should be moving slower. There must be an invisible mass providing extra gravity.</p>
        

        <h3>B. Gravitational Lensing</h3>
        <p>Massive amounts of Dark Matter bend the light from distant stars, acting like a giant magnifying glass in space. We see the light warping around "nothing," which tells us mass is present.</p>
        
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>3. THE COMPOSITION: WHAT IS IT?</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles):</strong> Heavy particles that pass through us like ghosts.</li>
            <li><strong>Axions:</strong> Ultra-light particles that could solve gaps in particle physics.</li>
            <li><strong>MACHOs:</strong> Massive objects like black holes (though this is now considered less likely).</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

